
Solve for X is a think tank project launched by Google to incite collaboration to solve global issues, "X" representing a remedy.[tpl]cite news|url=http://searchenginewatch.com/article/2144664/Solve-for-X-Googles-Answer-to-All-World-Problems|title=Solve for X: Googleâ€™s Answer to All World Problems|last=Rampton|first=John|date=February 7, 2012|work=Search Engine Watch|accessdate=February 11, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/65Nciko4c|archivedate=February 11, 2012[/tpl] The project kicked off on February 1 at a three-day convention at CordeValle Resort in San Martin, California. Solve for X talks were presented to 50 people, hosted by Google executives Eric Schmidt, Astro Teller, and Megan Smith.[tpl]cite news|url=http://idealab.talkingpointsmemo.com/2012/02/google-reveals-solve-for-x-website-for-ted-like-talks-series.php|title=Google Reveals 'Solve For X' Website For TED-Like Talks Series|last=Franzen|first=Carl|date=February 7, 2012|work=Talking Points Memo|accessdate=February 11, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/65NlVo9XY|archivedate=February 11, 2012[/tpl] The conventions are expected to occur "a few times a year".[tpl]cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-16925842|title=Google 'Solve for X' meetings target tech 'moonshots'|date=February 7, 2012|work=BBC News|accessdate=February 11, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/65Nlqqm8S|archivedate=February 11, 2012[/tpl] The website inaugurated on February 6, 2012.[tpl]cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/02/06/google-unveils-solve-for-_n_1258870.html|title=Solve For X, Google's Attempt At 'Moonshot Thinking,' Finally Opens To The Rest Of Us (VIDEO)|last=Bosker|first=Bianca|date=February 6, 2012|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=February 11, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/65NlgP2bt|archivedate=February 11, 2012[/tpl]
Solve for X has been likened to TED talks[tpl]cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/scitech/2012/02/06/google-unveils-secret-project-to-solve-worlds-biggest-problems/|title=Google unveils "Solve for X," a secret project to solve the world's biggest problems|date=February 6, 2012|work=Fox News|accessdate=February 11, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/65MSURZaw|archivedate=February 11, 2012[/tpl][tpl]cite news|url=http://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2399896,00.asp|title=Updated: Google Tackles 'Radical' Ideas Via 'Solve for X'|last=Horn|first=Leslie|date=6 February 2012|work=PC Magazine|accessdate=February 11, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/65MSb0C6L|archivedate=February 11, 2012[/tpl] since both projects host seminars by innovators, which can be viewed by others "vicariously" through the projects' respective websites. European director Bruno Giussani stated regarding Google's endeavor: "The world needs more ideas, not fewer and more commitment to sharing them freely and openly so that collectively we can test-run them and turn them into reality ... Google being at the origin of this, obviously technology and engineering will play a big role in Solve For X".
Solve for X was initially believed to be linked to the Google X Lab working on new technology such as web-connected appliances, driverless cars, and space elevators, but eWeek reported that Google X is wed to more realistic undertakings, not the "moonshot" solutions Solve for X was created to pursue.[tpl]cite news|url=http://www.eweek.com/c/a/Search-Engines/Google-Solve-For-X-Targets-Techs-Moonshot-Challenges-723626/|title=Google Solve For X Targets Tech's 'Moonshot' Challenges|last=Boulton|first=Clint|date=February 7, 2012|work=eWeek|accessdate=February 11, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/65NmkO48c|archivedate=February 11, 2012[/tpl]

